{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632820"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:45:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:45:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17444"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17444"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70932"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10134"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56399"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5449"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23834"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70932"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-month-old infant presents for their first vaccination appointment. The parents request to delay vaccinations until one year of age, stating they are concerned about overwhelming their child\u0027s immune system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the impact of delaying routine childhood vaccinations?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduces the risk of adverse reactions","Increases the period of disease vulnerability","Improves immune response to vaccines","Prevents immune system overload","Decreases the number of required doses"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe main impact of delaying routine childhood vaccinations is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreases the period of disease vulnerability\u003C/strong\u003E. The recommended vaccination schedule is designed to provide protection as early as possible while ensuring optimal immune response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces the risk of adverse reactions: \u003C/strong\u003Estudies have demonstrated no evidence that delaying vaccines reduces the likelihood or severity of adverse effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproves immune response to vaccines\u003C/strong\u003E: the recommended schedule is specifically timed to achieve optimal immune response based on immunological development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents immune system overload\u003C/strong\u003E: research shows that the infant immune system is capable of handling multiple simultaneous vaccinations without being overwhelmed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases the number of required doses\u003C/strong\u003E: the required number of doses for full immunisation remains the same regardless of when vaccines are administered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recommended vaccination schedule is based on epidemiological evidence considering disease risk, immune system maturity, and vaccine effectiveness. Delays increase the time children are susceptible to preventable diseases without providing any benefits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Delayed vaccination schedules increase the period of vulnerability to vaccine-preventable diseases.","The optimal timing of childhood vaccinations is based on balancing immune system maturity with disease risk.","Delaying vaccines does not reduce the risk of adverse effects but does increase disease susceptibility."],"references":["Smith PJ, Humiston SG, Parnell T, Vannice KS, Salmon DA. The association between intentional delay of vaccine administration and timely childhood vaccination coverage. Public Health Rep. 2010 Jul-Aug;125(4):534-41. doi: 10.1177/003335491012500408. PMID: 20597453; PMCID: PMC2882604.","Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56399"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17444"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56399"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T15:21:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T15:22:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10134"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70932"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"d